phases.content:
Modify `apps/desktop/src/components/terminal/TerminalPane.tsx` (current handler at lines 28-91) and `apps/desktop/src/components/terminal/TerminalTabs.tsx` (line 220 tooltip) to stop the window-level keydown handler from swallowing shell-relevant chords when an xterm has keyboard focus.

Changes in `TerminalPane.tsx`:

1. **Remove the Ctrl+T branch entirely** (currently lines 34-39 — `if (e.key === 't' || e.key === 'T') { e.preventDefault(); addTab(); return; }`). Ctrl+T is bash readline's `transpose-chars`; the terminal must see it untouched.

2. **Add a new Ctrl+Shift+T branch** for "new tab." Place it just before the existing Ctrl+W branch (so the modifier-shape ordering reads naturally). The check is `if (e.shiftKey && (e.key === 'T' || e.key === 't')) { e.preventDefault(); addTab(); return; }` — note that when Shift is held, the browser may report `e.key` as the uppercase `T`. Use the same case-insensitive check pattern other branches use.

3. **Gate the Ctrl+W branch** with an xterm-focus check. Replace the existing Ctrl+W block (lines 41-48) with:

   ```ts
   // Ctrl/Cmd + W: Close current tab — but ONLY when an xterm doesn't have focus.
   // In bash/zsh readline, Ctrl+W is `unix-word-rubout` (delete word backward).
   // Without this gate, typing Ctrl+W in the shell would kill the entire terminal.
   if (e.key === 'w' || e.key === 'W') {
     const target = e.target as HTMLElement | null;
     if (target?.closest('.xterm')) return;
     if (activeTabId) {
       e.preventDefault();
       removeTab(activeTabId);
     }
     return;
   }
   ```

   Using `.closest('.xterm')` catches both xterm's helper textarea and any descendant element inside `.xterm` containers. UI chrome (split bars, tab bar, settings) is *outside* `.xterm`, so Ctrl+W still works from those surfaces.

4. **Do not blanket-gate the entire handler.** The other shortcuts — Ctrl+Tab, Ctrl+Shift+Tab, Ctrl+Shift+H, Ctrl+Shift+| — must continue to fire even when the terminal has focus. Bash/zsh/PowerShell do not bind any of these chords, so they're safe to keep global. (This matches the verification line in the issue body: "Ctrl+Shift+H still splits even from a focused terminal.")

Changes in `TerminalTabs.tsx`:

5. **Update the "+" button tooltip** at line 220 from `title="New terminal (Ctrl+T)"` to `title="New terminal (Ctrl+Shift+T)"`.

No changes to `SettingsPage.tsx` in this issue. Sibling issue #160 (Ctrl+Z explainer) is the right home for any new "Keyboard shortcuts" reference block in Settings; adding one here would step on that scope.

Mac platform: the existing handler routes through `modifier = isMac ? e.metaKey : e.ctrlKey;` at line 30, so the new Ctrl+Shift+T and gated Ctrl+W inherit the same `modifier`-checked path. No mac-specific code needed.

Keep the existing dependency list on `useCallback` unchanged (`[activeTabId, addTab, removeTab, setActiveTab, splitTerminal, tabs]`).
